Raw dev notes -- Taming the Login Beast (or: My Battle with Browser Automation)

Okay, so this past week has been a deep dive into the browser automation API wrapper project. The whole point of this thing is to provide a super reliable, robust API for other internal services to interact with various web applications. Think of it as a highly specialized, bulletproof browser bot that can log into things and perform actions without human intervention, even when the UIs are... less than cooperative. It's all about making those tricky, manual web processes programmatic and dependable.

This sprint was almost entirely focused on making the login process truly unattended and resilient. First big win was actually a fix: I finally ditched using the system's Chrome installation and switched to Playwright's bundled Chromium. Man, that was a headache I didn't need. System Chrome versions, pathing issues, random updates breaking things – it was a constant source of "why isn't this working on the server but it's fine on my machine?" Switching to bundled just makes so much more sense for consistency.

Then it was all about the login flow itself. I built out this "self-healing auto-login fallback ladder." Sounds fancy, but really it just means I've got multiple strategies for finding login fields, clicking buttons, and generally navigating the login page, with fallbacks if the primary method fails. Because let's be real, web UIs are *not* consistent. One day the login button is `id="login-btn"`, the next it's `class="primary-action-button"`. This ladder tries a few things before giving up, which has been a game-changer for reliability.

2FA was the next big hurdle. Initially, I got it to auto-pick the SMS option on the 2FA challenge-selection page. That felt like a win! But then, after some testing, it became clear that the "phone-tap" method (where you just approve a notification on your phone) was actually way more reliable and faster. So, I went back and refactored it to *prefer* phone-tap, with SMS as the fallback. It's a small change, but it highlights how you have to iterate and optimize even after something "works."

The final piece of the login puzzle was getting TOTP (Time-based One-Time Password) fully unattended. This was a bit fiddly, dealing with the time-sensitive codes and making sure the input field was correctly identified and filled. And, because you can never account for *every* possible 2FA scenario, I also added a "Try-another-way escape" mechanism. If it hits an unexpected 2FA challenge, it'll try to find and click a "Try another way" or "Back" button to get to a known state or a different challenge option. It's a defensive move, but a necessary one.

Honestly, this whole period felt like a constant battle against flaky UIs and the inherent unpredictability of web pages. There were moments of pure frustration, especially when a perfectly working script would suddenly fail because some element's ID changed or a new interstitial popped up. But then, getting that "self-healing" logic to actually *work* and seeing the login flow go from start to finish, completely unattended, was incredibly satisfying. It's a good reminder that building robust systems often means anticipating failure and designing for resilience, not just happy paths. It's a lot like life, I guess – you gotta have a fallback plan.

Next up: Start tackling some of the post-login data extraction features.
